comments.message: Does this unquote the contents of $0? Or does the shell treat this differently because the "$0" is inside the $( )?

I know this is a corner case, but in case of path containing spaces, you have to double quote your variables.

Example:

(venv) seb@Guldan:~ $ cat foo\ \ \ \ bar/test.sh
#!/bin/bash
basename $0
echo $(basename $0)
basename "$0"
echo $(basename "$0")

(venv) seb@Guldan:~ $ ./foo\ \ \ \ bar/test.sh 
foo
foo
test.sh
test.sh


In addition, shellcheck raises a warning when double quotes are missing

Patch Set 2:

So, if I create a local mirror, I'd have to use negative priorities of -3 or lower?

Patch Set 2:

If you don't specidfy any priority a default is used:
See https://gerrit.legato/c/leaf/+/51713/3/src/leaf/core/download.py

- Local Filesystem: -10
- HTTPS: 20
- HTTP: 21
- Other protocole: 100

Without this patch, Swi remotes would have "20" because they are HTTPS.
I don't think this patch is mandatory, but I wanted to have SWI official remotes an higher priority than default HTTPS remotes, because I think most of users won't use a custom priority.

comments.message:
So using 0 here, and 1 underneath seems like it would have the same effect.
It might be good to consider the 'stable.json' as a reference, so 0.

At the moment I'm not sure what 0 means since this is going into negative values by default, and the default priorities based on protocols do not define anything for 0.

Should these be lower priorities (higher numbers) so that there's room for people to create their own (perhaps local) remotes that take precedence over these remotes without having to change the priorities of these remotes?  E.g., maybe use 10 and 20?
